EPISODE_NARRATIVE:
A low pressure system over the Ohio Valley early Sunday morning on December 1st, intensified as it moved northeast across Eastern Canada during early Monday morning.  A strong cold front that extended southwest from this low, swept across the local region early Monday morning.

Thunderstorms formed in the moist unstable airmass ahead of the cold front.  These storms produced  torrential rainfall that caused widespread small stream, street and poor drainage flooding.

Occasional rain began across the region during Saturday afternoon, November 30th.

Here are selected rainfall event totals for:

New York City:  from 1.53 inches at JFK Airport to 2.43 inches at Jamaica Estates.

Nassau County:  1.75 inches at Levittown.

Suffolk County:  from 0.89 inches at East Quogue to 2.15 inches at Mt. Sinai.

Westchester County:  from 1.59 inches at Ossining to 2.06 inches at Westchester County Airport.

Orange County:  from 1.25 inches at Walden to 2.48 inches at Sterling Forest.

A strong 958mb low near Attu drifted to a position 120 miles northeast of Attu and began to slowly weaken Monday.  By Tuesday, the center began to loop eastward and weaken more rapidly.  The front associated with this low moved into the central Aleutians Sunday morning then elonagated eastward into Bristol Bay and toward the southern tip of Kodiak Island Monday morning...weakening.  Strong winds, close to 45 mph, were observed around the low...especially along the west side of it...and inadvance of the front.

A small tornado touched down on the north side of Alexander City downing trees and power lines in a predominantly residential section.  Several structures sustained damage though most of it was fairly minor.  Reports indicated that two single-family homes sustained major damage with minor damage to an additional nine homes.

What was believed to be strong thunderstorm wind downed trees, power lines, and large billboards in a three mile long path along Interstate 85 east of Montgomery.  Damage began on the southside of the Interstate at exit 9 and extended along the Interstate crossing to the northside just before exit 11.  A Conoco quick stop mart and gas station was completely destroyed at exit 11.  Additional tree damage and minor roof damage extended about a mile to the east-northeast from exit 11 into the Techno Center industrial area.
A car was washed off the road and into a ditch along with tremendous street flooding in the Millbrook area in the southwestern part of the county.
Water flooded out of Gregor creek causing standing water on many roads.
Several roads closed due to high water.

Two mobile homes located along Highway 229 south of Tallassee were completely destroyed by what appeared to be straight-line wind.  The mobile homes were about 300 feet apart with a small, brick home situated between them with several trees around it.  There was no evidence of damage at the brick home or in the trees surrounding it.  No injuried occurred because no one was in either mobile home.

A slow moving cold front, coupled with a low pressure system that developed over West Virginia on the 1st and moved just northwest of New Jersey on the 2nd brought rain to the area from the 1st through the morning of the 2nd.  The rain was the heaviest during the early morning of the 2nd and caused some urban and poor drainage flooding.  River flooding was mainly confined to the Passaic and Raritan Basins.  Storm totals averaged between 1.5 and 2.5 inches with higher amounts in the northwest part of the state and lower amounts along the southeast shore.  Storm totals included 3.17 inches in Sparta (Sussex County), 2.89 inches in Blairstown (Warren County), 2.53 inches in Newton (Sussex County), 2.19 inches in Belvidere (Warren County), 1.76 inches in Pennsauken (Camden County), 1.75 inches in Brick Township (Ocean County), 1.68 inches in Estell Manor (Atlantic County), 1.61 inches in Millville (Cumberland County), 1.6 inches in Mount Holly (Burlington County) and 1.06 inches within Atlantic City.

A hay storage barn was destroyed, and several buildings sustained minor damage when thunderstorm wind struck an area on the north side of Highway 14 about 3.5 miles east of Tallassee in extreme southern Tallapoosa County.  EMA officials reported nine single-family dwellings sustained minor damage with one sustaining major damage.  Reports also indicated that three mobile homes were destroyed and five or six were blown off their foundation.  The damage path was 1 to 1.5 miles in length and fairly narrow ending near the intersection of Highway 14 and 49.  The steel siding from the barn was distributed in a rather classic fan pattern across the field to the east of the barn.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: High winds howled in and near the Front Range Foothills.  Wondervu in Northeast Gilpin County registered a peak wind gust to 105 mph (91 kts).  Elsewhere Eldora Ski Resort recorded a peak gust to 79 mph (69 kts) while Jefferson County Airport and a spotter 3 miles southeast of Estes Park reported gusts to around 70 mph (63 kts and 61 kts respectively).

High winds howled in and near the Front Range Foothills.  Wondervu in Northeast Gilpin County registered a peak wind gust to 105 mph (91 kts).  Elsewhere Eldora Ski Resort recorded a peak gust to 79 mph (69 kts) while Jefferson County Airport and a spotter 3 miles southeast of Estes Park reported gusts to around 70 mph (63 kts and 61 kts respectively).
Trees were blown down in Samson. Numerous power lines were reported down.
12 inches of snow at Discovery Ski Resort
A wind gust to 51 KTS was reported at Ft. Rucker.
Houston County authorities reported numerous trees blown down across the county.

A waterspout developed near Mid Bay Bridge along the north bank of Choctawhatchee Bay and moved ashore near exclusive Pippin Estates.  The resulting tornado moved along Lake Drive for about 1/3 of a mile.  Ten homes suffered roof damage, four of which had major structural damage.  Numerous fifty to one-hundred year old Live Oak and other trees were blown down.  Some of the trees fell across vehicles and homes.  Several boats were also blown ashore and damaged.  The tornado cut a path of about seventy-five yards wide and was estimated to be a weak F2.  There were no injuries.
Trees were downed just west of Villa Tasso. Other trees and power lines were reported down south of De Funiak Springs.

A fast-moving, very strong winter storm system blew through Utah wreaking havoc with the heavy travel at the end of the Thanksgiving weekend.   Gusty winds combined with periods of heavy snow to create local blizzard conditions.  Winds gusted from 30-40 mph.   Snowfall amounts were 3-7 inches in the valleys and 10-18 inches in the mountains.  The highest totals were in Filmore with 7 inches (valleys) and at several northern ski resorts with 18 inches (mountains).  Over 150 traffic accidents were reported statewide during this storm.  Numerous power outages and tractor-trailer rollovers were reported.  White-out conditions" occurred from Nephi to Cedar City on Interstate-15.  In Fillmore the Utah National Guard was forced to allow about 70 stranded motorists to spend the night in its armory.  All 7 motels in the area were already filled to capacity."

A strong 958mb low near Attu drifted to a position 120 miles northeast of Attu and began to slowly weaken Monday.  By Tuesday, the center began to loop eastward and weaken more rapidly.  The front associated with this low moved into the central Aleutians Sunday morning then elonagated eastward into Bristol Bay and toward the southern tip of Kodiak Island Monday morning...weakening.  Strong winds, close to 45 mph, were observed around the low...especially along the west side of it...and inadvance of the front.

An intense area of low pressure which moved from Indiana north across the Great Lakes, produced damaging winds over parts of eastern New York during the afternoon of December 1.  The wind downed trees and power lines in Warren, Washington, Saratoga, Schenectady, Albany, Rensselaer, Schoharie, Greene and Dutchess Counties.  Damage was most widespread in Saratoga, Warren and Rensselaer Counties.  At Waterford in Saratoga County, a tree fell on a trailer home and truck.  Approximately 2,000 customers lost power in the Capital District.

Strong winds accompanied the passage of a cold front during the afternoon hours. The high winds downed trees and power lines and damaged buildings. In Niagara Falls, the winds toppled a 60-foot Christmas tree and display. In Wilson, four power poles were knocked down. In Clymer, the winds blew the windows out of a home, blew off the door of a garage, and downed a fence. At the Buffalo Airport, a peak winds of 50 knots was recorded.

Damaging southwest winds moved through Berks County and the Lehigh Valley during the late afternoon of the 1st.

In Berks County, about 15,000 Pennsylvania Power and Light homes in the southwest part of the county lost power.  Spring Township was the hardest hit community with numerous downed trees reported.  A wind gust to 60 mph was measured in Vinemont at 4 p.m. EST.  Other communities losing power included Robesonia, Shillington, Sinking Spring, Womelsdorf and Wyomissing.  A wind gust to 58 mph was measured at the Reading Regional Airport.  Dozens of trees were uprooted within Reading.  In West Reading at 5 p.m. EST the wind peeled the roof from a rowhouse off and damaged another home's chimney.  In Robeson Township, the wind peeled a 50-foot-long roof from a machinery shed near the Green Hills Golf Course.  Another 2,600 General Power Utilities homes also lost power in the eastern part of the county around 4 p.m. EST in Birdsboro, Boyertown, Flying Hills and Topton.  Eighty percent of the customers had power returned by 9 p.m. EST.  A few trees were also uprooted in Bethel Township.       

In Lehigh County, several trees were knocked down in Coopersburg near the Pennsylvania State Route 519 Junction.  In Northampton County, about 1,500 Pennsylvania Power and Light customers lost power in Hanover and Bethlehem.  Downed trees blocked roadways in Easton and Hanover.  Trees also littered Pennsylvania State Route 611 north of Easton.

After 2 days of occasional rain, a final round of showers
dumped around a half inch of rain in less than 2 hours.
Route 39 was flooded by Knapp Creek near Huntersville, but
no dwellings were affected.  Also, streams feeding into the

the vicinity of Thornwood and Bartow. Later, a strong rise
occurred on the Greenbrier River, with a crest about a foot
below flood stage in the Buckeye area.

A storm dropped six to 12 inches of snow over northwest South Dakota.  The heaviest snow stretched from northeast Butte through northern Meade and Haakon counties.  Grand Electric Cooperative lost 268 poles in southern Perkins, Harding, northern Butte and Meade counties.  The damage was estimated at $194,000.  Numerous accidents occurred along Interstate 90, none with serious injuries.

Strong south winds and periods of heavy rain occurred ahead of an eastward moving cold front.  South winds reached a peak gust of 50 mph in Tiverton at 2:21 AM, 46 mph on Block Island , and 41 mph in downtown Providence during the next  several hours.

Rain, which fell from December 1st into the morning of the 2nd became heavy at times during the early morning of the second.  At the Philadelphia International Airport, 0.56 inches of rain fell between 2 a.m. and 3 a.m. EST.  The heavy rain caused urban flooding as well as flooding along the Frankford Creek.  At the Castor Avenue gage, the creek crested at 6.2 feet at 245 a.m. EST.  Flood stage is estimated at 5 feet.  Storm totals included 1.98 inches at the Northeast Philadelphia Airport and 1.78 inches at the Philadelphia International Airport.  No serious injuries or damage were reported.

A slow moving cold front, coupled with a low pressure system that developed over West Virginia on the 1st and moved just northwest of New Jersey on the 2nd brought rain to the area from the 1st through the morning of the 2nd.  The rain became heavy at times during the early morning of the 2nd. This led to flooding in the Passaic and Raritan Basins.

In Morris County, the Rockaway River both above and below the Boonton Reservoir exceeded their 5 foot flood stage.  Below the reservoir, the Rockaway was above flood stage from 4 a.m. EST on the 2nd through 2 a.m. EST on the 4th.  It crested at 6.3 feet at 8 p.m. EST on the 2nd.  Above the reservoir, the Rockaway was above flood stage from 1030 a.m. through 9 p.m. EST on the 2nd.  It crested at 5.2 feet at 315 p.m. EST on the 2nd.  The Passaic River at Pine Brook was above its estimated 19 foot flood stage from 2 a.m. EST on the 2nd through 830 p.m. EST on the 5th.  It crested at 19.4 feet at 8 p.m. EST on the 3rd.  Storm totals included 3.27 inches in Long Valley and 3.23 inches in Boonton.  No serious injuries or damage were reported. 

In Somerset County,  the Millstone River at Blackwells Mills was above its 9 foot flood stage from 11 a.m. EST on the 2nd through 10 a.m. EST on the 3rd.  It crested at 10.5 feet at 930 p.m. EST on the 2nd.  The Raritan River at Manville reached its 12 foot flood stage at 630 a.m. EST on the 2nd, crested at 15.7 feet at 515 p.m. EST on the 2nd and was back within bankfull at 4 a.m. EST on the 3rd.  Farther downstream, the Raritan at Bound Brook was above its 26 foot flood stage from 1130 a.m. EST on the 2nd through 730 a.m. EST on the 3rd.  It crested at 28.9 feet at 815 p.m. EST on the 2nd.  The flooding caused the closure of six roadways in Bedminster, Branchburg (three roads), Bridgewater, Franklin,  Hillsborough and Montgomery.  At least one home in Branchburg on New Jersey State Route 28 was damaged by flooding along the North Branch of the Raritan River.  Storm totals included 3.48 inches in Pottersville and 2.23 inches in Bridgewater.   

In Hunterdon County, the South Branch of the Raritan River reached its 8 foot flood stage at 6 a.m. EST on the 2nd, crested at 9.6 feet at 745 a.m. EST on the 2nd and was back within bankfull at 1045 a.m. EST on the 2nd.  Storm totals included 3.37 inches in Califon, 2.68 inches in Lambertville and 2.63 inches in Wertsville.  No serious injuries or damage were reported.

Rain that fell from the afternoon of December 1st into the morning of the 2nd caused flooding along the Christina River.  The heaviest rain fell during the early morning of the 2nd.  The Christina River at Cooch's Bridge crested at 10.6 feet at 515 a.m. EST on the 2nd.  It was above its 9 foot flood stage from 2 a.m. EST through 830 a.m. EST on the second. Storm totals included 2.20 inches in Pennyhill, 1.87 inches at the New Castle County Airport and 1.6 inches in Odessa.   No serious damage or injuries were reported.

A low pressure system over the Ohio Valley early Sunday morning on December 1st, intensified as it moved northeast across Eastern Canada during early Monday morning.  A strong cold front that extended southwest from this low, swept across the local region early Monday morning.

Lines of thunderstorms formed in the moist unstable airmass ahead of the cold front.  These storms produced numerous wind gusts from 58 MPH in East Orange of Essex County to 65 MPH at both Garwood and Berkeley Heights in Union County.

Thunderstorms also caused torrential rainfall.  The Ramapo River at Mahwah crested at 8.10 feet, just above its' 8.00 foot flood stage.  Small stream, street, and poor drainage flooding was widespread over Union, Passaic, and Bergen Counties.

Occasional rain began across the region during Saturday afternoon, November 30th.  Here are selected rainfall event totals:

For Passaic County:  from 1.82 inches at Wanaque to 4.51 inches at Ringwood.

For Bergen County:  from 2.00 inches at Franklin Lakes to 4.38 inches at Saddle River.

For Essex County:  from 1.83 inches at Newark Airport to 3.60 inches at Verona.

For Hudson County:  from 1.59 inches at Jersey City to 2.20 inches at Harrison.

For Union County:  from 2.15 inches at Canoe Brook to 2.61 inches at Elizabeth.

A slow moving cold front and a low pressure system that developed in West Virginia on the first and moved through Eastern Pennsylvania during the morning of the 2nd caused heavy rain and flooding along the Lehigh and Schuylkill Rivers.  The heaviest rain fell during the early morning on the second.  Storm totals averaged two to three inches, with some higher amounts in the Poconos.

The Lehigh River at Walnutport was above its 8 foot flood stage from 430 a.m. until 5 p.m. EST on the 2nd.  It crested at 9.5 feet at 9 a.m. EST on the second.  Minor flooding occurred along the Schuylkill River from Berne through Pottstown.  In Berne, the river reached its 12 foot flood stage at 3 a.m. EST on the 2nd, crested at 12.9 feet at 745 a.m. EST on the 2nd and was back within bankfull at 1 p.m. EST on the 2nd.  In Reading, the river was above its 13 foot flood stage from 1130 a.m. EST on the 2nd through 830 p.m. EST on the 2nd.  It crested at 13.7 feet at 430 p.m. EST on the 2nd.  In Pottstown, the river reached its 13 foot flood stage at 5 p.m. EST on the 17th, crested at 13.1 feet at 7 p.m. EST on the 17th and was back within bankfull at 9 p.m. EST.  No serious injuries or damage were reported.

Storm precipitation totals included 3.5 inches in Reading, 2.74 inches in Hamburg (Berks County), 2.52 inches in Honey Brook (Chester County), 2.5 inches in Vinemont (Berks County), 2.28 inches in Williams Township (Northampton County), 2.22 inches in Glenmoore (Chester County) 2.07 inches in Palm (Montgomery County), 1.98 inches in Green Lane (Montgomery County) and 1.89 inches at the Lehigh Valley International Airport.

The following day (December 3rd) a water rescue was performed along the Maiden Creek along Pennsylvania State Route 143 in Greenwich Township in Berks County.  Two men were canoeing on the Maiden Creek when it capsized.  One swam to safety, while the other clung to a tree for over an hour before being rescued.  The creek was within bankfull,  but the recent heavy rain had made it rougher and swelled its stage to about four feet above normal.

Heavy rain, which fell from December 1st into the morning of the 2nd caused flooding on some of the smaller streams as well as urban flooding in the county.  The heaviest rain fell after midnight on the 2nd.  Numerous roads were closed due to small stream and roadway flooding including the Netcong Circle.  The small stream flooding and heavy rain led to flooding along the Rockaway and Passaic Rivers.  Storm totals included 3.27 inches in Long Valley and 3.23 inches in Boonton.  No serious injuries or damage were reported.

Heavy rain, which fell during most of the day on the first into the morning of the second caused flooding of some of the smaller creeks and streams in Carbon and Monroe Counties.  The heaviest rain fell during the late evening of the first and the early morning on the second.  Storm totals averaged between three and four inches.  No serious injuries or damage were reported.  Representative storm totals included 4.00 inches in Saylorsburg, 3.56 inches in Long Pond, 3.55 inches in Lehighton, 3.3 inches in East Stroudsburg and 3.22 inches in Jundale.

A low pressure system over the Ohio Valley early Sunday morning on December 1st, intensified as it moved northeast across Eastern Canada during early Monday morning.  A strong cold front that extended southwest from this low, swept across the local region early Monday morning.

Lines of thunderstorms formed in the moist unstable airmass ahead of the cold front.  These storms produced  torrential rainfall that caused widespread small stream and river flooding.  The Mahwah River at Suffern rose to 4.52 feet.  Its' flood stage was 4.00 feet.  The Hackensack River left about 2 1/2 feet of water on sections of Route 59, forcing the closure of both east bound lanes in West Nyack.

Occasional rain began across the region during Saturday afternoon, November 30th.  Here are selected rainfall event totals for Rockland County:  from 1.59 inches at West Nyack to 2.74 inches at Suffern.

Rain, which fell from December 1st into the morning of the 2nd caused stream and creek flooding in Delaware County.  The heaviest rain fell during the early morning of the 2nd.  At the Philadelphia International Airport, 0.56 inches of rain fell within the hour between 2 a.m. and 3 a.m. on the 2nd.  Chester Creek near Chester was above its 8 foot flood stage from 4 a.m. EST to 7a.m. EST on the 2nd.  It crested at 8.6 feet at 6 a.m. EST.  No serious injuries or damage were reported.  Storm totals included 2.85 inches in Crum Creek, 2.25 inches in Chadds Ford and 1.78 inches at the Philadelphia International Airport.

A slow moving cold front and a low pressure system that developed in West Virginia on the first and moved through Eastern Pennsylvania during the morning of the 2nd caused heavy rain and flooding along the Lehigh and Schuylkill Rivers.  The heaviest rain fell during the early morning on the second.  Storm totals averaged two to three inches, with some higher amounts in the Poconos.

The Lehigh River at Walnutport was above its 8 foot flood stage from 430 a.m. until 5 p.m. EST on the 2nd.  It crested at 9.5 feet at 9 a.m. EST on the second.  Minor flooding occurred along the Schuylkill River from Berne through Pottstown.  In Berne, the river reached its 12 foot flood stage at 3 a.m. EST on the 2nd, crested at 12.9 feet at 745 a.m. EST on the 2nd and was back within bankfull at 1 p.m. EST on the 2nd.  In Reading, the river was above its 13 foot flood stage from 1130 a.m. EST on the 2nd through 830 p.m. EST on the 2nd.  It crested at 13.7 feet at 430 p.m. EST on the 2nd.  In Pottstown, the river reached its 13 foot flood stage at 5 p.m. EST on the 17th, crested at 13.1 feet at 7 p.m. EST on the 17th and was back within bankfull at 9 p.m. EST.  No serious injuries or damage were reported.

Storm precipitation totals included 3.5 inches in Reading, 2.74 inches in Hamburg (Berks County), 2.52 inches in Honey Brook (Chester County), 2.5 inches in Vinemont (Berks County), 2.28 inches in Williams Township (Northampton County), 2.22 inches in Glenmoore (Chester County) 2.07 inches in Palm (Montgomery County), 1.98 inches in Green Lane (Montgomery County) and 1.89 inches at the Lehigh Valley International Airport.

The following day (December 3rd) a water rescue was performed along the Maiden Creek along Pennsylvania State Route 143 in Greenwich Township in Berks County.  Two men were canoeing on the Maiden Creek when it capsized.  One swam to safety, while the other clung to a tree for over an hour before being rescued.  The creek was within bankfull,  but the recent heavy rain had made it rougher and swelled its stage to about four feet above normal.

The Neshaminy Creek at Langhorne, reached its 9 foot flood stage at 530 a.m. EST on the 2nd, crested at 10.7 feet at 1 p.m. EST on the 2nd and was back within bankfull at 430 p.m. EST on the 2nd. Storm totals included 3.24 inches in Doylestown, 2.87 inches in Neshaminy Falls, 2.74 inches in Springtown, 2.3 inches in Southampton, 2.28 inches in Perkasie, 2.2 inches in Fricks, 2.18 inches in Sellersville, and 1.94 inches in New Hope. A strong and slow moving cold front brought heavy rains to much of central New York from the late afternoon of the 1st into the early morning hours of the 2nd.  Generally, rainfall amounts of 1.5 to 3.5 inches were observed across the region.
     Heavy rainfall combined with already saturated soil conditions to produce widespread flash flooding in the Susquehanna region and Western Catskills.  Streams and creeks first overflowed their banks in Tioga and eastern Chemung counties late in the evening of the 1st.  Several road closures and bridge washouts were reported in these counties.  As the band of heavy rain shifted eastward during the night, flash flooding began shortly after midnight in most of the Susquehanna region.  Significant small stream flooding occurred in northern portions of Broome county and throughout Cortland county.  Route 26 was closed for a time just north of Whitney Point in Broome County.  In the pre-dawn hours of the 2nd, flooding problems started from Otsego county southward through the Catskills.  Countywide stream and creek flooding hit Otsego county, with over a foot of water on roadways in the town of Hartwick.  In the Catskills, major stream and roadway flooding developed in the towns of Franklin and Claryville in southern Delaware and northern Sullivan counties respectively.  By midday on the 2nd, all area creeks and streams had receded back within their banks.
     Main stem river flooding began to surface within the Susquehanna basin just before sunrise on the 2nd.  The Tioughnioga river near Cortland in Cortland county was the first to overflow its banks.  Later that morning, minor lowland flooding occurred from Unadilla downstream to Waverly.  Some flooding also occurred along the Chenango river from Sherburne to Chenango Forks.  In all instances, flooding was insignificant with only a few roads immediately adjacent to the river taking on water.  
     Flooding also occurred on the East Branch of the Delaware river on the Beaver Kill Creek at Cooks Falls and near Callicoon.
Road closures and basement flooding were reported in these areas.   
     By early in the morning on the 5th, all river points had fallen below flood stage.

A slow moving cold front, coupled with a low pressure system that developed over West Virginia on the 1st and moved just northwest of New Jersey on the 2nd brought rain to the area from the 1st through the morning of the 2nd.  The rain became heavy at times during the early morning of the 2nd. This led to flooding in the Passaic and Raritan Basins.

In Morris County, the Rockaway River both above and below the Boonton Reservoir exceeded their 5 foot flood stage.  Below the reservoir, the Rockaway was above flood stage from 4 a.m. EST on the 2nd through 2 a.m. EST on the 4th.  It crested at 6.3 feet at 8 p.m. EST on the 2nd.  Above the reservoir, the Rockaway was above flood stage from 1030 a.m. through 9 p.m. EST on the 2nd.  It crested at 5.2 feet at 315 p.m. EST on the 2nd.  The Passaic River at Pine Brook was above its estimated 19 foot flood stage from 2 a.m. EST on the 2nd through 830 p.m. EST on the 5th.  It crested at 19.4 feet at 8 p.m. EST on the 3rd.  Storm totals included 3.27 inches in Long Valley and 3.23 inches in Boonton.  No serious injuries or damage were reported. 

In Somerset County,  the Millstone River at Blackwells Mills was above its 9 foot flood stage from 11 a.m. EST on the 2nd through 10 a.m. EST on the 3rd.  It crested at 10.5 feet at 930 p.m. EST on the 2nd.  The Raritan River at Manville reached its 12 foot flood stage at 630 a.m. EST on the 2nd, crested at 15.7 feet at 515 p.m. EST on the 2nd and was back within bankfull at 4 a.m. EST on the 3rd.  Farther downstream, the Raritan at Bound Brook was above its 26 foot flood stage from 1130 a.m. EST on the 2nd through 730 a.m. EST on the 3rd.  It crested at 28.9 feet at 815 p.m. EST on the 2nd.  The flooding caused the closure of six roadways in Bedminster, Branchburg (three roads), Bridgewater, Franklin,  Hillsborough and Montgomery.  At least one home in Branchburg on New Jersey State Route 28 was damaged by flooding along the North Branch of the Raritan River.  Storm totals included 3.48 inches in Pottersville and 2.23 inches in Bridgewater.   

In Hunterdon County, the South Branch of the Raritan River reached its 8 foot flood stage at 6 a.m. EST on the 2nd, crested at 9.6 feet at 745 a.m. EST on the 2nd and was back within bankfull at 1045 a.m. EST on the 2nd.  Storm totals included 3.37 inches in Califon, 2.68 inches in Lambertville and 2.63 inches in Wertsville.  No serious injuries or damage were reported.

A strong and slow moving cold front brought heavy rains to northeast Pennsylvania from the early evening of the 1st into the early morning of the 2nd.  Generally, from 1 to 3 inches of rain were observed across the region.
     Heavy rainfall combined with already saturated soil conditions to produce flash flooding in Bradford county.  Late in the evening of the 1st, the Towanda Creek came out of its banks with several roadways in the town of Canton inundated.  After midnight, the Sugar Run Creek also left its banks with several ensuing bridge and road washouts.  By mid morning on the 2nd, all area creeks and streams had receded back within their banks.  
     Main stem river flooding followed around daybreak on the 2nd in the Susquehanna basin of northeast Pennsylvania.  Minor lowland flooding occurred from Towanda downstream to Wilkes-Barre.  Other than a few brief evacuations of trailer parks in Wyoming county, only flood plain areas right along the river took on any substantial water.
     By the pre-dawn hours of the 5th, all river points had fallen below flood stage.

Low pressure produced 1 to 2 inches of rain across much of eastern New York during December 1 through the morning of December 2.  Rainfall totals around 3 inches occurred over parts of the upper Hudson River Basin and in the Catskills.  This amount of rainfall during the late fall season resulted in flooding across much of the region.  In Fulton County, the Cavadutta Creek flooded in the Town of Johnstown and flooding was also reported in the Caroga Lake area.  In Montgomery County, roads in low lying areas were flooded in the Towns of Florida, Palatine and Canajoharie.  State Highway 30 was flooded in the Town of Florida.  In Schoharie County, flooding occurred in the Towns of Cobleskill, Richmondville and Esperance.  In the Village of Cobleskill, West Street and Quarry Street were washed out.  Basements were flooded in Barnerville due to the Cobleskill Creek.  In the Town of Richmondville, Mickle Road and Warnerville Cutoff Road were closed.  Flooding was widespread in Ulster County.  Roads were closed in the Towns of Denning, Hardenburgh, New Paltz, Kingston, Ulster, Woodstock and Saugerties.  A state of emergency was declared in the Town of Shandaken during the morning hours of December 2.  McKinley Hollow Road and Lost Cove Road were severely damaged.  Old route 28 was flooded between Phoenicia and Mount Tremper.  The Town of Hardenburgh also suffered severe road damage.  In the Town of Woodstock, roads were flooded when the Sawkill overflowed its banks.  The Esopus Creek crested 2.5 feet above flood stage above the Ashokan Reservoir.  The lower Esopus Creek went approximately 3 feet over flood stage when water spilled over the top of the Ashokan Dam.  Orlando Street and Sandy Road in the Town of Ulster were evacuated along the Esopus Creek.  Damage was minor during this flooding event along the entire Esopus Creek.  In Hamlton County, the Sacandaga River went 2 feet above flood stage at Hope.  In Washington County, many roads were flooded and washed out.  In the Village of Whitehall, Broadway was closed for several hours.  In the Town of Fort Ann, Hogtown Road and Shelving Rock Road were badly washed out.  Many roads were also flooded and washed out in Warren County.  The Towns of Thurman, Bolton and Stony Creek were hardest hit.  State Highway 8 in the Town of Horicon, had a 30 foot section washed out across both lanes.  State Highway 9N in the Town of Bolton was closed until late afternoon on December 2.  The Mohawk River flooded in southern Herkimer County, Montgomery County and in Schenectady County.  The flooding was fairly minor.  The river went 1 foot above flood stage at Little Falls and crested near flood stage in Schenectady.  Roads at the industrial park near Little Falls were flooded.  In Montgomery County, the Tribes Hill Bridge in Fort Hunter was closed as a steel gate on Lock 12 under the bridge was forced open.  In Schenectday County, River Road was flooded in Niskayuna and some flooding occurred in the Stockade region in Schenectady.  Minor flooding occurred along the Schoharie Creek in Schoharie, Montgomery and western Schenectady Counties.  The creek reached the 6 foot flood stage at Burtonville in Montgomery County and some flooding occurred in the Lost Valley.  In Schoharie County, Redling and Bielfeldt Roads were flooded along the creek.  Minor flooding occurred along the Hoosic River in southern Washington County and northern Rensselaer County.  At Buskirk in Rensselaer County, Firehouse Road was closed between the covered bridge and County Route 67.  Minor flooding occurred along the Hudson River in Saratoga and Washington Counties.  Fort Edward in Washington County and Waterford and the Stillwater Flats in Saratoga County sustained minor flooding.  Along the Moose River in northern Herkimer County, minor flooding occurred at McKeever.  The West Canada Creek flooded in southern Herkimer County from the Hinckley Reservoir downsteam to the Mohawk River.  The flooding was confined to low lying areas.
River flooding occurred on the Kennebec and Piscataquis Rivers due to 3 to 5 inches of rain  combined with snowmelt.  Little damage occurred along the Kennebec River.

An intensifying frontal low, moving northeast across the north Pacific, deepened to 949 mbs...centering 300 miles south of King Salmon at 9 am Tuesday.  The front elongated east and northeast across the Gulf of Alaska Tuesday.  The low moved to 250 miles south of Seward at 9 pm Tuesday as a strong 945mb center.  Thereafter, the center began an east northeast drift across the Gulf of Alaska...slowly weakening to a 970 mb center near Sitka at 9 am Thursday.  Easterly wind gusts reached 63 mph at Middleton Island Tuesday in advance of the front.  Gusts from 50 to 60 mph were reported near Cordova and at several buoys in and near Prince William Sound Tuesday. Also...just in advance of the front.. northerly winds reached a peak of 64 mph at Kodiak on Tuesday.  On the back side of the low...strong northwest winds gusted to 60 mph at Kodiak on Friday.  Westerly wind gusts were above 40 mph at Cold Bay for 8 consecutive days from Wednesday through the next Thursday...reaching 61 mph on Friday.

An 86 year old white female died of hypothermia in her home.

An upper-level trough moved across the northern Great Basin developing snow across extreme northern Utah.  Though the northern mountains did not receive warning criteria snowfall, most northern valleys did.  Generally 4-8 inches of snow was reported with this system.  The greatest amount was 8 just north of Logan in the Cache valley.  There were 100 known traffic accidents responsible for 25 injuries."

Heavy rainfall amounts of 2 to 3 inches on the first and second of the month combined with some snow melt in the Connecticut River Basin to produce runoff, which resulted in minor flooding of several small streams and flooding along the Connecticut River below Thompsonville.  The South Branch of the Park River...a small stream...reached flood stage of 10 feet at Hartford at 5:40 AM on December 2nd, crested at 11.1 feet at 6:30 AM, then fell below flood stage at 8:00 AM.  The North Branch of the Park River reached flood stage of 8 feet at Hartford at 6:00 AM on the 2nd, crested at 9.4 feet at 10:30 AM, and fell below flood stage at 11:00 PM.  The Connecticut River reached flood stage of 16 feet at Hartford at 5:00 PM on December 3rd, crested at 18.6 feet 24 hours later on the 4th, then fell below flood stage at 8:00 AM on December 6th.
Eight to nine inches of snow at DeBorgia and Lookout Pass Ski Area.

The Ohio River crested 2 to 3 feet above flood stage at several locations. At Cairo, where the flood stage is 40 feet, the Ohio crested at 42.93 feet on the 9th. At Shawneetown, where flood stage is 33 feet, the river crested at 36.1 feet on the 8th. The river was above flood stage for about a week at both locations. Flooding was confined mainly to parks and agricultural bottomlands. Fort Defiance State Park near Cairo was closed due to flooding of roads.
Peak wind at Kneeland 45 mph.

A Pacific storm brought high winds to the North and Central Oregon Coast. On the North Coast, Netarts reported sustained winds of 50 mph gusting to 70 mph, Newport 40 mph gusting to 75 mph and Tillamook 46 mph. On the Central Coast Sea Lion Caves reported 51 mph sustained winds with gusts to 75 mph.

This winter storm produced accumulations of 18 inches and more in the higher elevations of the Sierra Nevada and about 5 inches in the Lake Tahoe basin.  In the Shasta-Cascades, snow fell at the 1500 foot level, causing the closure of Interstate 5 during the evening of the 4th. In Lake county, 166 customers lost power as trees laden with snow fell on power lines the night of the 4th.

On December 4th through the 5th another winter storm moved through the state.  This storm produced 7 to 14 inches of new snow in Zones 11 and 13.  Some totals included:  New Meadows at 14 inches, Fairfield at 12 inches, and 10 inches at Cascade, Placerville and Council.  This storm produced 2 to 6 inches of new snow in the Southwest valleys.  Six inches fell at Payette and Weiser, 3 inches at New Plymouth and 2 inches fell at Boise and Parma.  In the Magic Valley, 6 inches fell at Gooding, Hagerman, Shoshone and Murphey Hot Springs.  In the Southwest Highlands, 8 inches fell at Silver City and 6 inches fell at Delmar Mine and Castleford.  In the North, winds gusting to 70 mph at Grangeville caused zero visiblity in blowing snow.   As the storm moved East, one foot of snow fell at McCammon in Bannock county and winds gusting to 58 mph occured just north of Pocatello.  Schools were closed in Idaho Falls and I84 was closed from Burley to Pocatello.  In Oneida county, a foot of new snow also fell and schools were closed due to blowing snow, many roads were impassable.  Schools were also closed in Cassia county.  Most locations across the southeast received 4 to 10 inches of new snow.

CZ_NAME_STR: LARIMER COUNTY BELOW 6000 FEET / NW WELD COUNTY (ZONE)
EPISODE_NARRATIVE:
A persistent westerly flow aloft over Colorado brought yet another round of high winds to areas in and near the Front Range Foothills.  Several locations reported hurricane force winds with peak gusts from 100 to 120 mph.  Seven hundred residents in the foothills were left without power for nearly 4 hours as high winds downed trees and power lines.  Communities affected by the outage included:  Beaver Brook, Blue Valley, Conifer, Estes Park, Evergreen and Floyd Hill.  In addition, a wall of a building under contruction in Lafayette was toppled, a semi-truck was blown over near the Boulder turnpike damaging a concrete barrier, and a 60-ft tree crushed a parked pickup truck at a Denver residence.

CZ_NAME_STR: ALAMOSA VICINITY / CENTRAL SAN LUIS VALLEY BELOW 8500 FT (ZONE)
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong winds occurred from the Sangre de Cristo mountains and east from early morning of the 4th through most of the day, as a powerful jet stream moved across Colorado. Sustained winds of 30 to 50 mph prevailed across the entire area before tapering off by late afternoon of the 5th. Damaging wind gusts began early morning of the 5th.  Winds gusts to between 70 and 100 mph in the mountains west of and into Colorado Springs.  In El Paso County a 70 foot Ponderosa pine fell on a house, and numerous fences and other outbuildings were damaged.  Extensive damage occurred across the Wet Mountain Valley.  Numerous power lines, smaller buildings, house and vehicle windows, and large trees were destroyed or damaged, as winds gusted over 100 mph.  The Pines Ranch, 10 miles northwest of Westcliffe in the northwest Wet Mountain Valley reported hundreds of large Ponderosa pines blown down and snapped off. In Stonewall, in Huerfano county, winds were estimated over 100 mph,  damaging Picketwire Lodge.

A cool unstable airmass produced thunderstorms over Westrern Oregon. A small tornado touched down in North Eugene inflicting an estimated 50,000 dollars in damage to a residential neighborhood, mostly from downed trees falling on houses.
Snow, sleet, and freezing rain fell in the mountains and northern foothills resulting in general accumulations of 1 to 3 inches, with 4 inches in Avery county. Numerous traffic accidents occurred.

A storm system combined with a moist westerly flow to spread heavy snow to much of the state.  The valleys received from 6-11 inches while the mountains from 1-2 feet.  The highest total for the mountains was at the Park City ski resort where 23 inches accumulated.  Bountiful measured 11 inches for highest in the valleys.  The wet snow helped to trigger 6 avalanches during and shortly after the storm.  A 37-year old man snowmobiling near Bountiful Peak was killed when he was overcome by one of these slides.  There were also about 100 traffic accidents with 20 known injuries during this storm.

The wet snow helped to trigger 6 avalanches during and shortly after the storm.  A 37-year old man snowmobiling near Bountiful Peak was killed when he was overcome by one of these slides.  There were also about 100 traffic accidents with 20 known injuries during this storm.

Five to 8 inches of snow fell.
A severe thunderstorm blew a tree across a power line along Kingston Pike and one across the road at Amherst and Ball Camp Pike.  Other reports of trees down in west part of county.
A severe thunderstorm moved across McGhee-Tyson airport.  A wind gust of 50 knots was recorded at 1746 EST.

A vigorous upper-level disturbance combined with available moisture and marginally cold air to produce a swath of wet snow across the Virginia piedmont.  Counties with mean elevation below 750 feet received between 1 and 3 inches, though isolated higher spots noted substantially greater totals.  Such was the case in Loudoun Co (VAZ042) and Prince William (VAZ052) Cos, where mean snow totals were 2 inches, but local high spots received between 4 and 6 inches.

A vigorous upper-level disturbance combined with available moisture and marginally cold air to produce a swath of heavy, wet snow across much of western Virginia from the Blue Ridge through the highlands, including most of the Shenandoah Valley.  Accumulations were highly dependent on elevation.  In general, western counties with mean elevations above 750 feet received 4 or 5 inches.  However, many locations above 2500 feet received 6 or more inches of snow.

The snow, which accumulated in a 3 to 4 hour period, covered many area highways, resulting in numerous accidents.  Two particularly hard-hit counties were Augusta and Rockingham.  The road problems were exacerbated by the fact that this was the first major snow of the season; few, if any, abrasives had been previously applied.  The event, which arrived at the tail end of the evening commute, snarled traffic and induced dozens of accidents.  A woman was killed when her vehicle flipped on icy roads in Craigsville (VAZ025).  Numerous accidents involved multiple vehicles.  Damage from the storm was minimal; only a few power outages were reported by Virginia Power and the Rappahannock Electric Cooperative.

A vigorous upper-level disturbance combined with available moisture and marginally cold temperatures to produce a swath of heavy wet snow across much of eastern West Virginia.  In general, accumulations were 4 or 5 inches, with only Grant Co (WVZ048) and Jefferson Co (WVZ053) receiving average accumulations of 3 inches.  The highest totals were in Pendleton Co (WVZ054), where 6 inches fell in Franklin, Sugar Grove, and Upper Tract.

Totals exceeding 8 inches were likely at elevations above 2500 feet.

A low pressure system developed over South Carolina the afternoon of the 5th.  As it quickly intensified and moved northeast (It passed just east of the New Jersey coast the morning of the 6th.), the precipitation associated with it changed from rain to snow across the higher terrain of the Poconos the evening of the 5th and over the higher terrain of northeast Berks County during the early morning of the 6th.  As the storm intensified during the early morning hours of the 6th, so did the precipitation.  The heaviest snow fell between about 2 a.m. and 8 a.m EST.  The snow also was very elevation dependent.  While heavy snow fell over the higher terrain, mainly just rain fell in Reading.  A mixture of rain and snow fell in Stroudsburg where less than one inch of snow accumulated.

Snowfall accumulations in Monroe County reached 19 inches in Tobyhanna and 15 inches in Mount Pocono.  The Mount Pocono borough had to declare a state of emergency after the heavy snow and jacknifed tractor trailers forced the closures of Interstates 80 and 380.  Traffic was diverted through the borough on Pennsylvania State Routes 611 and 940.  Dozens of weather related accidents were reported by state police throughout the Poconos.  Other snowfall accumulations included 13 inches in Long Pond, 11 inches in Pocono Lakes and 8 inches in Jundale in Carbon County.  The snow was heavy and very wet and pulled down numerous power lines.  About 38,000 homes and businesses in Pennsylvania, Power and Light's service area in Northeast Pennsylvania lost power with Monroe and Wayne Counties hit the hardest.  The hardest hit locations within Monroe County were Blakeslee, Mount Pocono and Mountainhome.  There were still 800 homes without power as of 5 p.m. EST on the 7th.  In Carbon County, classes were cancelled in the eastern part of the county in Penn Forest and Kidder Townships.    

In Berks County, six to eight inches of snow fell over the higher terrain of the eastern part of the county from Fleetwood to Hereford Township.

A vigorous upper-level disturbance combined with available moisture and marginally cold air to produce a swath of wet snow from the Maryland piedmont to the Potomac Highlands.  Only Allegany Co (MDZ002) received widespread accumulations of 4 inches or more; the remaining affected counties received average accumulations between 1 and 3 inches.

Accumulations were highly dependent on elevation, especially in the foothills.  In Frederick Co (MDZ004), lower terrain received 2 or 3 inches.  However, along the western mountains, up to 9 inches may have fallen in Wolfsville.  The same was likely true in neighboring Washington (MDZ003) Co.  A similar effect occurred farther east, where 2 inches fell in western and northern Montgomery and Howard Cos (MDZ009>010), but plain rain fell in the southern and eastern portions.  In general, the dividing line of accumulating snow was at 750 feet above sea level.

A vigorous upper-level disturbance combined with available moisture and marginally cold air to produce a swath of heavy, wet snow across much of western Virginia from the Blue Ridge through the highlands, including most of the Shenandoah Valley.  Accumulations were highly dependent on elevation.  In general, western counties with mean elevations above 750 feet received 4 or 5 inches.  However, many locations above 2500 feet received 6 or more inches of snow.

The snow, which accumulated in a 3 to 4 hour period, covered many area highways, resulting in numerous accidents.  Two particularly hard-hit counties were Augusta and Rockingham.  The road problems were exacerbated by the fact that this was the first major snow of the season; few, if any, abrasives had been previously applied.  The event, which arrived at the tail end of the evening commute, snarled traffic and induced dozens of accidents.  A woman was killed when her vehicle flipped on icy roads in Craigsville (VAZ025).  Numerous accidents involved multiple vehicles.  Damage from the storm was minimal; only a few power outages were reported by Virginia Power and the Rappahannock Electric Cooperative.
